{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621325"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:52:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:52:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16706"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75560"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3202"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22247"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75560"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of speech difficulties following a stroke. He has hypertension and type 2 diabetes, for which he takes amlodipine and metformin. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His speech is non-fluent with agrammatism, syntactic comprehension deficits, and phonological errors. He has stuttering but mostly normal comprehension of spoken and written language.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of aphasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Receptive aphasia","Conduction aphasia","Expressive aphasia","Global aphasia","Transcortical sensory aphasia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Eexpressive aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E (Broca\u0027s aphasia), characterised by non-fluent speech with agrammatism but relatively preserved comprehension. The key features are effortful speech production, poor grammar, and phonological errors while maintaining the ability to understand language.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReceptive aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E (Wernicke\u0027s aphasia) is characterised by fluent but meaningless speech, and poor comprehension of language.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduction aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by fluent spontaneous speech with good comprehension, but difficulty repeating words and phrases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobal aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most severe form, affecting all aspects of language including both expression and comprehension. This patient\u0027s preserved comprehension rules out global aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscortical sensory aphasia\u003C/strong\u003E presents with impaired comprehension but preserved repetition and speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe location of the lesion in expressive aphasia is typically in Broca\u0027s area, part of the inferior frontal gyrus in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere, the left for the vast majority of the population. The non-fluent speech with preserved comprehension is the hallmark of this condition, making it distinct from other types of aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Expressive or Broca\u0027s aphasia is characterised by non-fluent, effortful speech with agrammatism and preserved comprehension","Broca\u0027s area is in the left frontal lobe in the vast majority of the population","Assessment of aphasia requires evaluation of fluency, comprehension, repetition, naming, reading and writing abilities."],"references":["Sheppard SM, Sebastian R. Diagnosing and managing post-stroke aphasia. Expert Rev Neurother. 2021 Feb;21(2):221-234. doi: 10.1080/14737175.2020.1855976. Epub 2020 Dec 10. PMID: 33231117; PMCID: PMC7880889.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Tippett DC, Niparko JK, Hillis AE. Aphasia: Current Concepts in Theory and Practice. J Neurol Transl Neurosci. 2014 Jan;2(1):1042. PMID: 24904925; PMCID: PMC4041294."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T10:21:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T10:23:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75560"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"